notes.note:
Hi Michael,
I’ve been working with our Claims team for this GAP claim.
In your original calculation in the GAP worksheet, the figure that was calculated was -$1,394.43, which is to infer that there is no GAP claim to pay.  However, in reviewing the documents, we came up with a different amount, which is $5.16.  The reason for this difference was the fact that there was an incorrect figure that was used for “Original Loan Amount”, the “Extended Warranty Refund” field was entered as a positive value instead of a negative value, and the “Deductible Reimbursement” field was entered as a negative value instead of a positive value.  In terms of any potential payout, I feel that $5.16 is too small an amount to send, and should be rendered as a “no GAP payout” so please confirm this calculation and let me know if you agree.
I have entered in the correct values in the attached spreadsheet, “CGW GAP Claim Wheaton…” with some a few accompanying notes for the future.  I have also attached the original GAP worksheet, “198241BlankRMACalculator” for reference. 
Additionally, our Claims team identified something that could be added to the GAP worksheet.  Because the GAP payout calculation would involve the lower amount between MSRP and Vehicle Purchase Price for new vehicles and the lower amount between CBB and Vehicle Purchase Price for used vehicles, I have added those fields into the GAP worksheet so that our Claims team can have visibility to those amounts. 
I have also updated and tailored the GAP worksheet, including a tab with a list of creditors, for this GAP program and used the Teri Wheaton claim details as an example in the attached worksheet, “CGW GAP Claim Breakdown – Updated”.  Going forward, please use the new spreadsheet and let me know if you have any questions.
Thank you,
Wayne Cheng
